('{205EEAD8-1C8F-4620-AE08-EF02589DC981}', 24, '<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>\r<rdf:RDF xmlns:rdf="http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#" xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/" xmlns:dct="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xmlns:dcmiBox="http://dublincore.org/documents/2000/07/11/dcmi-box/" xmlns:ows="http://www.opengis.net/ows">\r<rdf:Description rdf:about="http://services.arcgisonline.com/ArcGIS/rest/services/Elevation/USGS_Elevation_US/GlobeServer">\r<dc:identifier>http://services.arcgisonline.com/ArcGIS/rest/services/Elevation/USGS_Elevation_US/GlobeServer</dc:identifier>\r<dc:title>Elevation/USGS_Elevation_US</dc:title>\r<dc:description>This globe service presents elevation for the contiguous United States at a resolution of about 30 meters. Vertical units are measured in meters. The data is from the National Elevation Dataset (NED) produced by the United States Geological Survey (USGS). NED is designed to provide national elevation data in a seamless form with a consistent datum, elevation unit, and projection. For more information on this map, including the terms of use, visit us &lt;a href=&quot;http://goto.arcgisonline.com/maps/Elevation/USGS_Elevation_US &quot; target=&quot;_new&quot;&gt;online&lt;/a&gt;.</dc:description>\r<dct:references scheme="urn:x-esri:specification:ServiceType:ArcGIS:GlobeServer">http://services.arcgisonline.com/ArcGIS/rest/services/Elevation/USGS_Elevation_US/GlobeServer</dct:references>\r<dc:subject>GlobeServer</dc:subject>\r<dc:subject>liveData</dc:subject>\r<dc:subject>service</dc:subject>\r<dc:subject>globe</dc:subject>\r<dct:abstract>\r<rdf:value rdf:resource="service.layername">Elevation (30m)\r</rdf:value>\r</dct:abstract>\r</rdf:Description>\r</rdf:RDF>', NULL),
('{23EF2FE4-BA8E-4E01-9CC1-267227508EB2}', 10, '<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>\r<rdf:RDF xmlns:rdf="http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#" xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/" xmlns:dct="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xmlns:dcmiBox="http://dublincore.org/documents/2000/07/11/dcmi-box/" xmlns:ows="http://www.opengis.net/ows">\r<rdf:Description rdf:about="http://services.arcgisonline.com/ArcGIS/rest/services/Demographics/USA_Median_Household_Income/MapServer">\r<dc:identifier>http://services.arcgisonline.com/ArcGIS/rest/services/Demographics/USA_Median_Household_Income/MapServer</dc:identifier>\r<dc:title>USA Median Household Income</dc:title>\r<dc:description>This thematic map presents the median household income in the United States in 2010. The 2010 Median Household Income is an estimate of income for the calendar year 2009. Income amounts are expressed in current dollars, including an adjustment for inflation or cost-of-living increases. The median is the value that divides the distribution of household income into two equal parts. These data are ESRIs 2010 estimates. The geography depicts states at greater than 25m scale, counties at 1m to 25m scale, Census Tracts at 250k to 1m scale, and Census Block Groups at less than 250k scale. The map has been designed to be displayed with semi-transparency of about 50% for overlay on other base maps, which is reflected in the legend for the map.  For more information on this map, including our terms of use, visit us online at http://goto.arcgisonline.com/maps/Demographics/USA_Median_Household_Income</dc:description>\r<dc:creator>ESRI</dc:creator>\r<dct:references scheme="urn:x-esri:specification:ServiceType:ArcGIS:MapServer">http://services.arcgisonline.com/ArcGIS/rest/services/Demographics/USA_Median_Household_Income/MapServer</dct:references>\r<dct:references scheme="urn:x-esri:specification:ServiceType:ArcIMS:Metadata:Thumbnail">http://services.arcgisonline.com/ArcGIS/rest/services/Demographics/USA_Median_Household_Income/MapServer/export?size=256,256&amp;f=image</dct:references>\r<dc:subject>MapServer</dc:subject>\r<dc:subject>liveData</dc:subject>\r<dc:subject>service</dc:subject>\r<dc:subject>United States</dc:subject>\r<dc:subject>2010</dc:subject>\r<dc:subject>income</dc:subject>\r<dc:subject>demographics</dc:subject>\r<ows:WGS84BoundingBox>\r<ows:LowerCorner>-179.999999 4.99999999999998</ows:LowerCorner>\r<ows:UpperCorner>-60.0 72.0</ows:UpperCorner>\r</ows:WGS84BoundingBox>\r<dct:abstract>\r<rdf:value rdf:resource="mxd.comments">This thematic map presents the median household income in the United States in 2010. The 2010 Median Household Income is an estimate of income for the calendar year 2009. Income amounts are expressed in current dollars, including an adjustment for inflation or cost-of-living increases. The median is the value that divides the distribution of household income into two equal parts. These data are ESRIs 2010 estimates. The geography depicts states at greater than 25m scale, counties at 1m to 25m scale, Census Tracts at 250k to 1m scale, and Census Block Groups at less than 250k scale. The map has been designed to be displayed with semi-transparency of about 50% for overlay on other base maps, which is reflected in the legend for the map.  For more information on this map, visit us online at http://goto.arcgisonline.com/maps/Demographics/USA_Median_Household_Income\r</rdf:value>\r<rdf:value rdf:resource="mxd.subject">demographics\r</rdf:value>\r<rdf:value rdf:resource="service.layername">USA Median Household Income\r</rdf:value>\r<rdf:value rdf:resource="service.layername">Block Groups\r</rdf:value>\r<rdf:value rdf:resource="service.layername">Tracts\r</rdf:value>\r<rdf:value rdf:resource="service.layername">Counties\r</rdf:value>\r<rdf:value rdf:resource="service.layername">States\r</rdf:value>\r</dct:abstract>\r</rdf:Description>\r</rdf:RDF>', NULL),
('{25FB71E9-3B39-4DDF-B439-C91B55344C90}', 45, '<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>\r<rdf:RDF xmlns:rdf="http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#" xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/" xmlns:dct="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xmlns:dcmiBox="http://dublincore.org/documents/2000/07/11/dcmi-box/" xmlns:ows="http://www.opengis.net/ows">\r<rdf:Description rdf:about="http://services.arcgisonline.com/ArcGIS/rest/services/World_Topo_Map/MapServer">\r<dc:identifier>http://services.arcgisonline.com/ArcGIS/rest/services/World_Topo_Map/MapServer</dc:identifier>\r<dc:title>World Topographic Map</dc:title>\r<dc:description>This map is designed to be used as a basemap by GIS professionals and as a reference map by anyone. The map includes administrative boundaries, cities, water features, physiographic features, parks, landmarks, highways, roads, railways, and airports overlaid on land cover and shaded relief imagery for added context. The map provides coverage for the world down to a scale of ~1:72k. Coverage is provided down to ~1:4k for the following areas: Australia and New Zealand; India; Europe; Canada; Mexico; the continental United States and Hawaii; parts of southern Africa including Botswana, Lesotho, Namibia, South Africa, and Swaziland; and parts of South America including Argentina, Brazil, Chile, Columbia, and Venezuela. Coverage down to ~1:1k and ~1:2k is available in select urban areas. This basemap was compiled from a variety of best available sources from several data providers, including the U.S. Geological Survey (USGS), U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) , U.S. National Park Service (NPS), Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO), Department of Natural Resources Canada (NRCAN), GeoBase, Agriculture and Agri-Food Canada, DeLorme, NAVTEQ, and Esri.\n\nFor more information on this map, including our terms of use, visit us online at http://goto.arcgisonline.com/maps/World_Topo_Map</dc:description>\r<dc:creator>Esri</dc:creator>\r<dct:references scheme="urn:x-esri:specification:ServiceType:ArcGIS:MapServer">http://services.arcgisonline.com/ArcGIS/rest/services/World_Topo_Map/MapServer</dct:references>\r<dct:references scheme="urn:x-esri:specification:ServiceType:ArcIMS:Metadata:Thumbnail">http://services.arcgisonline.com/ArcGIS/rest/services/World_Topo_Map/MapServer/export?size=256,256&amp;f=image</dct:references>\r<dc:subject>MapServer</dc:subject>\r<dc:subject>liveData</dc:subject>\r<dc:subject>service</dc:subject>\r<dc:subject>World</dc:subject>\r<dc:subject>Global</dc:subject>\r<dc:subject>Europe</dc:subject>\r<dc:subject>North America</dc:subject>\r<dc:subject>South America</dc:subject>\r<dc:subject>Southern Africa</dc:subject>\r<dc:subject>Australia</dc:subject>\r<dc:subject>New Zealand</dc:subject>\r<dc:subject>India</dc:subject>\r<dc:subject>2013</dc:subject>\r<ows:WGS84BoundingBox>\r<ows:LowerCorner>-179.999988540844 -85.0</ows:LowerCorner>\r<ows:UpperCorner>179.999988540844 85.0000000000001</ows:UpperCorner>\r</ows:WGS84BoundingBox>\r<dct:abstract>\r<rdf:value rdf:resource="mxd.subject">topographic, topography, administrative boundaries, cities, water features, physiographic features, parks, landmarks, highways, roads, railways, airports, land cover, shaded relief imagery\r</rdf:value>\r<rdf:value rdf:resource="mxd.category">imageryBaseMapsEarthCover (Imagery, basemaps, and land cover)\r</rdf:value>\r<rdf:value rdf:resource="service.layername">Topographic Info\r</rdf:value>\r<rdf:value rdf:resource="service.layername">Elevation (m)\r</rdf:value>\r<rdf:value rdf:resource="service.layername">Elevation (ft)\r</rdf:value>\r<rdf:value rdf:resource="service.layername">Slope\r</rdf:value>\r<rdf:value rdf:resource="service.layername">Aspect\r</rdf:value>\r<rdf:value rdf:resource="service.layername">Places Info\r</rdf:value>\r<rdf:value rdf:resource="service.layername">Place Names (Country Level)\r</rdf:value>\r<rdf:value rdf:resource="service.layername">Place Names (State Level)\r</rdf:value>\r<rdf:value rdf:resource="service.layername">Place Names (County Level)\r</rdf:value>\r<rdf:value rdf:resource="service.layername">Place Names (City Level)\r</rdf:value>\r<rdf:value rdf:resource="service.layername">Citations\r</rdf:value>\r</dct:abstract>\r</rdf:Description>\r</rdf:RDF>', NULL),
('{2C5318EF-5BAD-419D-A7AD-86228C817970}', 6, '<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>\r<rdf:RDF xmlns:rdf="http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#" xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/" xmlns:dct="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xmlns:dcmiBox="http://dublincore.org/documents/2000/07/11/dcmi-box/" xmlns:ows="http://www.opengis.net/ows">\r<rdf:Description rdf:about="http://services.arcgisonline.com/ArcGIS/rest/services/Demographics/USA_Diversity_Index/MapServer">\r<dc:identifier>http://services.arcgisonline.com/ArcGIS/rest/services/Demographics/USA_Diversity_Index/MapServer</dc:identifier>\r<dc:title>USA Diversity Index</dc:title>\r<dc:description>This thematic map summarizes racial and ethnic diversity in the United States. The index shows the likelihood that two persons, chosen at random from the same area, belong to different race or ethnic groups. The index ranges from 0 (no diversity) to 100 (complete diversity). For example, the diversity score for the U.S. is 60 which means there is a 60 percent probability that two people randomly chosen from the U.S. population would belong to different race or ethnic groups. These data are ESRIs 2010 estimates. Diversity in the U.S. population is increasing. The states with the most diverse populations are California, Hawaii and New Mexico. The map has been designed to be displayed with semi-transparency of about 50% for overlay on other base maps, which is reflected in the legend for the map. The geography depicts states at greater than 25m scale, counties at 1m to 25m scale, Census Tracts at 250k to 1m scale, and Census Block Groups at less than 250k scale.  For more information on this map, including our terms of use, visit us online at http://goto.arcgisonline.com/maps/Demographics/USA_Diversity_Index</dc:description>\r<dc:creator>ESRI</dc:creator>\r<dct:references scheme="urn:x-esri:specification:ServiceType:ArcGIS:MapServer">http://services.arcgisonline.com/ArcGIS/rest/services/Demographics/USA_Diversity_Index/MapServer</dct:references>\r<dct:references scheme="urn:x-esri:specification:ServiceType:ArcIMS:Metadata:Thumbnail">http://services.arcgisonline.com/ArcGIS/rest/services/Demographics/USA_Diversity_Index/MapServer/export?size=256,256&amp;f=image</dct:references>\r<dc:subject>MapServer</dc:subject>\r<dc:subject>liveData</dc:subject>\r<dc:subject>service</dc:subject>\r<dc:subject>United States</dc:subject>\r<dc:subject>2010</dc:subject>\r<dc:subject>diversity</dc:subject>\r<dc:subject>demographics</dc:subject>\r<ows:WGS84BoundingBox>\r<ows:LowerCorner>-179.999988540844 4.99999999999997</ows:LowerCorner>\r<ows:UpperCorner>-60.0 72.0</ows:UpperCorner>\r</ows:WGS84BoundingBox>\r<dct:abstract>\r<rdf:value rdf:resource="mxd.comments">This thematic map summarizes racial and ethnic diversity in the United States. The index shows the likelihood that two persons, chosen at random from the same area, belong to different race or ethnic groups. The index ranges from 0 (no diversity) to 100 (complete diversity). For example, the diversity score for the U.S. is 60 which means there is a 60 percent probability that two people randomly chosen from the U.S. population would belong to different race or ethnic groups. These data are ESRIs 2010 estimates. Diversity in the U.S. population is increasing. The states with the most diverse populations are California, Hawaii and New Mexico. The map has been designed to be displayed with semi-transparency of about 50% for overlay on other base maps, which is reflected in the legend for the map. The geography depicts states at greater than 25m scale, counties at 1m to 25m scale, Census Tracts at 250k to 1m scale, and Census Block Groups at less than 250k scale.  For more information on this map, visit us online at http://goto.arcgisonline.com/maps/Demographics/USA_Diversity_Index\r</rdf:value>\r<rdf:value rdf:resource="mxd.subject">demographics\r</rdf:value>\r<rdf:value rdf:resource="service.layername">USA Diversity Index\r</rdf:value>\r<rdf:value r